search:spring-boot+kotlin-coroutines-adv.content:
- Use `./mvnw clean install` to build your Spring Boot Kotlin project.
- Ensure you have the latest version of Kotlin and Spring Boot in your `pom.xml`.
- Configure coroutines in your `application.yml` or `application.properties`:
  ```yaml
  spring:
    task:
      execution:
        pool:
          core-size: 10
          max-size: 20
          queue-capacity: 500
  ```
- Use `@EnableWebFlux` to enable reactive web support in your Spring Boot application.
- Implement coroutines using the `suspend` keyword and `runBlocking`, `launch`, or `async`.
- For testing, use `Testcontainers` for integration tests:
  ```kotlin
  @Testcontainers
  class MyIntegrationTest {
      @Container
      private val myDatabase = PostgreSQLContainer("postgres:latest")

      @Autowired
      lateinit var myService: MyService

      @BeforeEach
      fun setUp() {
          // Initialize database and data
      }

      @AfterEach
      fun tearDown() {
          // Clean up resources
      }

      @Test
      fun testMyFunction() = runBlocking {
          val result = myService.myFunction()
          assertEquals(expected, result)
      }
  }
  ```
- Ensure you have the latest versions of `spring-boot-starter-webflux` and `kotlinx-coroutines-core` in your dependencies.
- Use `@WebFluxTest` for testing reactive controllers without starting the full application context.
